div.div:
Update vendor.js file and refactor layout properties
Updated the vendor.js.LICENSE file to include copyright information for the Pusher JS Library. The CalendarLayout in the Orchid Layouts was also refactored, removing the description property and adding a slug property instead. An additional change was made to formatting in the confirm.blade.php partial view.

Refactor animation property in dashy.js
Updated the animation attribute in dashy.js file under vendor/fluffici. The change enhances the flow and consistency of animations by adjusting animation duration timings.

Refactor calendar controller and update dependencies
Refactored the calendar controller JavaScript file to improve code maintainability and enhance debugging instructions. Also incorporated the FullCalendar and Pusher libraries into the webpack.mix.js file, resulting in updates to other dependencies including dashy.js and vendor.js. These changes aim to improve calendar type handling.

Add FullCalendar and Pusher JS libraries and update calendar controller
Added FullCalendar and Pusher JavaScript libraries to webpack.mix.js dependencies. Also made improvements to calendar controller by cleaning the code, enhancing debugging info, and refining logic for different calendar type handling. As part of these changes, the dashy.js and vendor.js files were updated as reflected in mix-manifest.json updates.

Correction incorrect namespace in Calendar layout
Fixed incorrect namespace usage in CalendarLayout and TestCalendar files. The correct namespace has been updated to Orchid\Screen\Layouts\Calendar from vendor\orchid\platform\src\Screen\Layouts\Calendar, resolving issues related to class loading and immproving adherence to PSR-4 autoloading standard.

Correct namespace casing in CalendarLayout and TestCalendar
Fixed case sensitive namespace issue in both CalendarLayout and TestCalendar classes. Previously, the lowercased "app" namespace was used, which caused the classes not to load correctly. This has been corrected to "App" for proper class loading and better adherence to PSR-4 autoloading standard.
